A common trigger for ex-smokers: driving or getting stuck in traffic. You could chew sugarless gum or listen to the radio to combat your craving. What else could you do instead of smoking when you're behind the wheel? #control

55. Great smoking-substitutions can help you break the smoking associations you've developed.  Tell us which one of these replacements to smoking you like best and tell us how it breaks your mental cycle around smoking #feeling healthy:o Rather than smoke in the car, drink your coffee in the car insteado Go to a place where you are not allowed to smokeo Have a healthy snack or chew gum
Snack
One of the best ways to combat a nicotine craving is to keep your hands busy! How can you plan to keep your hands occupied when you get hit with a sudden urge to smoke? #feeling healthy

Go to my other addiction, the internet lol

Practice makes perfect! Today, everytime you feel the urge to light up, wait at least 10 minutes and practice using a smoking substition. What did you choose to do, and how helpful was it to curb your craving? #feeling healthy

When your cravings are getting bad, call someone you trust and tell them how you’re feeling and that you don’t want to smoke. Try it out and let us know how it went. #feeling healthy
My boyfriend is quitting with me now!!! Extra motivation, Calling him helps a lot <3

Half the battle of quitting is breaking cigarette associations. So change up your routines: drink your morning coffee outside or switch to tea. How are you going to mix things up to make them new again? #control
What would you miss most if you quit smoking for good? #TDII
The peace and quiet! I only smoke when my kids are asleep or I'm on break at work. It's my Me time
Thanks for sharing 10036. You smoke to make a relaxing situations or a break more enjoyable. I am curious: And what are things you don't like about smoking?
The aftertaste sucks
Yes I can see that. How to you feel about quitting at the moment? How motivated are you to give it a try?
I'm currently trying to move out of a bad situation and out of state so that will not work as of right now lol

Wow yeah that sound tough. I can see how quitting smoking would not be on the very top of your agenda at the moment. One suggestion though: Maybe you can think about other nice things you can reward yourself with in a relaxing situation, as an alternative to smoking. Here are some tips. Anything useful for you?
I miss lighting a smoke up after finishing up some hard work, and really enjoying the satisfaction that I can just kick back and relax.
Thanks for sharing 10052 - same question for you: And what would you be happy to get rid of?

I think smoking is kind of like lying/tricking your brain. When you are having a shitty day, you make up for it by having a smoke. On the other hand, if you're having a really good day, you make it even better by enjoying a smoke on top of it. In this sense, smoking is a way for you to create 'false' reward for yourself. By smoking, you are artificially stimulating the reward pathways in your brain, making you expect rewards where there should not be any. I think that's not a very positive way to wire your brain, so quitting smoking will help me unlearn this and also be a chance for me to improve my self-control.

That's a very good observation, 10052 - and great to hear that you are seeing this as a challenge that you can learn something from. The only thing I would like to add to what you just said is that after smoking for a while, the only thing smoking will do for you is really just helping you get rid of your withdrawal for a short time. So essentially you are in a state of withdrawal for most of the time and smoking will get you back to normal. So if you quit for good in the end you will be in your 'normal' state all of the time - isn't that nice to know?!

I definitely would like my 'normal' state to be my default mode - I'm working towards day 42 so I'm on my way to that. However, I do believe in rewards when they are truly earned - so I hope to one day be able to enjoy a cigarette on special occasions without it becoming a regular habit. But personally, I think that's a level up in difficulty from not smoking at all, so it's something I hope to work up to in the future.

Great job!! I think you are making the right call for now 10052 - better safe than sorry until you are really rid of your habit! An alternative future scenario may very likely be that you may find cigarettes losing their appeal and don't taste as nice as you remembered them. But in any case I just recommend to be careful so you don't end up taking it up again.
Ok guys, I've got to run - see you next week!

Yes, thanks for the advice Dr. Thrul! And yeah, you're totally right that cigs don't taste very good the first time you smoke them after a while - unfortunately, that hasn't deterred me from relapsing before. You're also right that trying 'controlled smoke' will increase my chance of relapsing, so I don't plan to try that any time soon as per your advice. However, having the level of self-control to 'controlled smoke' is what I strive for as my 'ideal self' in the far future. I know I am definitely not there yet and still have a long way to go. I really appreciate your advice and guidance today - they are helping me work towards developing this self-discipline!

The following post was made by a successful quitter: 'I hired a cleaning service to clean my whole house. I figured it didn’t cost any more than my cigarettes would have, and I felt like it was a gift to myself for making a fresh, nonsmoking start'.  Would you ever do the same as this ex-smoker? #reinforcement
I don''t smoke in the house, so this isn't directly relevant to me. But I think it's a great idea to renovate your environment!

Never smoke inside, but when i moved into a house where an old man had smoked inside for god knows how long... I sprayed everything down like 4 times before it stopped coming off yellow!!! Definitely a realization

data.message: Hi guys, I am about to start session 2. Stop by if you are interested in getting some more advice around effective smoking cessation strategies tailored to your specific needs!
I have posted the content of today's session on the wall of this  event. Come check it out if you are interested. See you next week!
Hi guys, what is currently your biggest smoking trigger? #TDII
I'd say after finishing something that took a lot of work or effort - I really like that 'phew, I'm finished, I'm gonna relax now' cigarette.
Yeah, that's a good one. What else can you do to reward yourself after a job well done?
What's realistically always available is savoring the fact I worked hard and am done, or looking forward to something fun that might be happening later.
That's great 10052 and I agree, just taking some time to really savor the feeling of accomplishment can already go a long way! By the way: Are you still smokefree? How long has it been for you now?
21 days!

If you don't mind answering, there are a couple things I want to ask you: 1) What advice do you have for staying motivated over the long term to be smoke-free? I successfully give it up for ~2 months for lent every year, but it's really a lot more difficult to stay smoke free for a longer, more permanent timescale. 2) What is your advice for coping with relapse? My experience is I kind of give up just start smoking whatever I feel like, which I think a lot of others could relate to.

Those are great questions 10052! For long term success I think it is crucial to reward yourself and establish habits that go against smoking. For example a healthy lifestyle with healthy food and enough exercise. Also you should pay attention to your body becoming more healthy because you stopped inhaling all of those toxic chemicals. Also a great long term strategy can be to safe the money you previously spent on cigarettes and reward yourself with something really nice, for example a vacation or something you always wanted (I'm sure you can think of something).

As for your second question: Lapses can always happen and that's nothing to be afraid of. It's really up to you though if they become full blown relapses and that's something that is up to you to decide. What I always tell my patients is that when you have a lapse you should really see it as such. Right away get rid of the cigarettes and paraphernalia you may have bought and immediately continue with your quit attempt.
Does that sound like something that may help you?
Also, I think you should consider your long-term health benefits - the longer to you stay smoke-free, the better it gets :)

That's all I have for today guys. Feel free to stop by my next smoking cessation advice session tomorrow! I will talk more about high risk situations and remedies for craving/withdrawal in the tomorrow's session.
Thanks for the replies Dr Johannes Thrul, I will definitely keep them in mind!
Drinking
Definitely stress! I'm having to move once again for the 2nd time in 4 months and I'm craving one right now... Plus the stress put on me by my aunt whose house I'm leaving. It's crazy in my life atm

Here are five really practical substitutions for smoking. Which of these easy replacements would fit into your life? Would any of you use more than one of these? #feelinghealthyo Chew on a toothpick or coffee stirrero Tell yourself that you can beat this urgeo Hold a pencil, rubber ball or worry beadso Take a shower- you can’t smoke in there!o Surf the internet
Personally, I don't really get oral fixation - in fact, I find that to sometimes even be triggering. Doing things to keep my mind off the desire to smoke is the most helpful for me.

data.description: Hi everyone! The next Q&A session will be tomorrow. See you then!

data.message: Holding out on your next smoke is great practice for when you quit smoking. Try it out for a day and report back how it felt to know you can handle more time without smoking. #feelinghealthy

ive tried that before as i tapered for previous quitting attempts - i guess i did it more with the mentality that id smoke fewer cigarettes in a given day, which would spread them out more throughout the day
It feels good to take a break but I always go back
.. This sounds good for someone one who smokes quite a bit!

The following post was made by a successful quitter: 'I focused every day on another way that I felt better. One day, I’d notice how much easier it was to breathe, and another day I would realize how I could walk up the stairs without getting winded. Reminding myself each day about what I was getting out of quitting made it seem worthwhile'. How do you think you'll notice your body getting healthier when you quit? #reinforcement
Not hacking my lungs up after running
Post what happened when you told your one (or a few) friends about your plan to quit. #support

they were glad to hear it and asked me how i was doing it. the ones i told are nonsmokers - as glad as they were to hear i was quitting, ive also noticed they dont really know how to best support me because they've never had to try to quit before
Mine wished me luck, almost felt it was halfhearted but maybe thats me lol
They don't believe me lol

Ready to commit to quitting? Pick a date to quit smoking for good! Post it here, or create a group event and invite everyone in this group. Everytime you check Facebook, you’ll be reminded that someone is making the change with you. #freeyourself
already started 2 weeks ago!
Is this your first attempt at quitting? If not, what worked/didn’t work for you in the past? Share your story here.  #freeyourself
Iv quit a couple of times and the thing that makes me go back is seeing my friends smoking.
No, I've tried a few times and also give it up every year for Lent. Cold turkey each time. Staying positive and trying to get myself to see in a long term perspective helped a lot.
Cold turkey. It helps when i look at the money im saving

I've quit cold turkey when i found out i was pregnant with both my kids but with the stress of my son being 3 months early and in the NICU, and my relationship failing after both pregnancies, it brought out a ton of stress and i started again. If i can better my life for me and my kids then it'll be easier to stay away

Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studies strategies like counseling or nicotine replacement therapy (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit.  #e-cig
People think they look good though. I don't, I think it's annoying!
Theyre are a bit of a trend right now
Only because of the flavors and most places allow you to smoke them inside. Plus they have such awesome color combinations that make people want to smoke more because it's 'healthier'.

Yesterday we asked you to tell us how confident you were that you COULD quit smoking if you wanted to. What would it take to get you from the number you said yesterday to ONE NUMBER HIGHER? #motivation
If i didnt work around smokers. Or if i got them to say they wont let me bum
How do you feel about your quitting now? Still feeling committed to staying smoke free? #TDII

Yes - the first week was pretty bad (I haven't had withdrawal hit me like that before, even on previous attempts), but it has been significantly easier the second week! I would like to one day enjoy the occasional smoke on special occasions without it becoming a habit, but for now the goal is to stay completely smoke free

Great job 10052 - keep up the good work! Yes withdrawal is a funny animal and can be very different during different quit attempts. Glad to hear it's getting easier though. What works for you to cope with craving and withdrawal?

by the way: I think your decision to stay completely smoke free is a good one, especially at first. The problem with 'controlled' smoking is that not very many people are able to do it - and we basically have no idea who is able to do it and who will relapse back to regular smoking.

Breathing exercises by default if I feel a craving - it's just so quick, easy and simple that I have no reason not to spend 30 seconds doing this. For the kind of craving that doesn't just go away, I also think about the long-term disappointment I'll have after caving in compared to the short-term pleasure I'd get from a smoke. I also acknowledge myself for doing a good job of getting this far.   Yup, I'm 100% with you on the controlled smoking (didn't realize there was a term for it) - it will take even more discipline to do than not smoking, period. I hope I'll work up to that point one day once I've stayed smoke free for a while.

That's it for today guys. Stay tuned for another one of the special smoking cessation advice sessions next week. I will talk more about triggers, high risk situations, and about ways to deal with those. See you!
Yay cold turkey ^.^
We understand that stopping smoking is not easy. On a scale of 1-10, how confident are you that you COULD quit smoking if you tried? #motivation
A 5 because I just bought my own tobacco to roll my own cigs so it's really tempting
Still8, but im surrounded by people who smoke and give me then when asked. Makes it hard. I feel bad for bumming and eant to buy my own pack, which would make me smoke more
Still working on it
We’ve been posting about different NRTs for a few days. Which one do you think would be best to help you quit smoking and why? #beingconscious
maybe one of the over the counter NRTs, as they are easier to get and just 'try out' to see if i like it or not
I'd like to say cold turket but thats what ive been trying and keep bumming cigs off people at work.. So maybe the gum, because its unpleasant taste would make me only rake it as needed
What have you heard about bupropion to help people stop smoking? Would you consider taking a medication to help you quit? #beingconscious
Yeah because it looks easy and as long as it's not expensive why not
No, i have a lot of addicts in my family and it would not be wise for me to take pills for an addiction
I feel like I'd rather try other options before thinking about getting prescribed an antidepressant.
I wouldnt want to transfer my addiction i want to end it
Happy New Year everyone! How is 2015 treating you so far? Have you tried making any changes to your smoking? #TDII
yup, made it past day 8 so far!
Great job 10052! What is your strategy and how are you making it work?
I've got to run guys - I wanted to give you some additional suggestions for how to deal with withdrawal symptoms.
Also, next week I will start offering 6 additional smoking cessation sessions. Attending these sessions will increase your chances of quitting - so feel free to stop by and check them out. See you!
I haven't smoked in 4 days because it's just way too cold outside!
^ really, the cold weather is working in my favor

When withdrawal symptoms are at their worst, a nasal spray can be a quick and convenient way to pack a punch to those cravings. Would you ever use a nicotine nasal spray? Why or why not? #beingconscious
No that sounds awful
I've accidently had liquid nicotene come out of my ecigs, and i tastes so gross. Wonder if this would be nasty too
Would you consider using a nicotine inhaler to quit smoking? Why or why not? #beingconscious
I feel like it'd be really strong, im so used to the hookah type pens with flavoring
This over-the-counter Nicotine Replacement Therapy looks like cough drops and can help alleviate withdrawal symptoms during work or class. Would you try this method? Why or why not? #beingconscious
Yeah if it tastes good
Hmm never seen this, but yes as long as it tastes decent (not too much nicotene)
What have you heard about nicotine gum? How do you think the gum will help you? #beingconscious  http://smokefree.gov/mg-nicotine_gum.aspx
Can take when youre stressed, and only as needed
Because i feel like it tastes a little weird so i wouldnt want to take it if i didnt need to
What have you heard about the patch as a Nicotine Replacement Therapy. http://smokefree.gov/mg-nicotine_patch.aspx Would you ever use it? #beingconscious
I heard that for a light smoker like me, it might hit a little bit too hard compared to having a cigarette.
yes iv heard of it but i would never do it because I don't think it works,  My sister used those a couple of times and it didn't work for her once she took them off
I just know this is what people tried alot when my mom was trying to quit, and it would work for awhile and then not. But thats probably got to do with other factors as well

Asking you to go out and party, even though they know drinking is a trigger, would NOT be helpful. Joking about how long you’ll stay on the wagon would NOT be helpful. What other things could you ask your friends NOT to do to keep you on the right path? #support
Not offer me cigarettes when they know I'm trying to quit
Not say yes when i ask to bum a cig :p
Many people associate the beginning of a new year with change. Do you guys have any resolutions for the New Year? #TDII
I've got to run guys - Happy new year everyone and I look forward to working with you in 2015!
Still trying to quit, to help my toher resolution - to be healthy. Includes eating right, exercising Etc

Now that you’ve shared about your top reasons for quitting smoking, let’s consider your top reason NOT to quit. Post your #1 Con for quitting here and tell us why it’s your biggest concern. Finish this sentence: 'I want to quit smoking, but I'm worried that ________.' Feel free to discuss with other group members concerns about quitting.  #freeyourself
The number one reason why I wouldn't want to quit is because I like the feeling of being able to have a cigarette. The fixation of smoking is what keeps me smoking I guess.
Nice to have a cig when youre stressed.
Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
With the holidays coming up I’d be interested to find out more about your smoking. Any specific smoking triggers coming up for you?

I've got to run guys. Here are some options that can help you deal with cigarette cravings that may come up. Happy Holidays everyone! http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/quit-smoking/in-depth/nicotine-craving/art-20045454
Helpful article^

data.description: I'll be doing another session Q&A this week. Looking forward to seeing you there!

data.message: How do you feel about a medication that changes its dose of nicotine to match the intensity of your withdrawal symptoms? Would any of you consider using varenicline? #beingconscious

I like the physical smoking, this would feel pointless. I like spending a few minutes smoking when i feel stressed. I dont think popping a pill in would feel the same. smoking makes you breathe in and out. Breathing is a big part of Meditation. So in a way, i see smoking as my 'meditation'.

I definitely agree with 10054 that nicotine substitutes (I guess aside from vaping) can't replace the actual act and feel of smoking. However, when you are trying to quit, you are probably most likely to cave in to smoke when you are the most stressed out. I think a nicotine replacement may not be as 'nice' as having an actual smoke, but can at least take some of the edge off of an especially bad craving so that not caving in becomes more manageable.

data.message: Reducing the amount you smoke can lead to quitting . After looking into gradual reduction, http://www.livestrong.com/article/196587-how-do-i-stop-smoking-gradually/  do you think this method could be right for you on your quit date? #beingconscious
I'd be worried it'd just hurt my goal. Because if youre only slowing it down, then that means theres nicotene in your posession to tempt you

Historically, most successful quitters chose this approach. Learn about withdrawal symptoms and cravings here: http://www.webmd.com/smoking-cessation/quit-smoking and tell us if you plan to use this method. Why or why not? #beingconscious
Ive used this method before and it worked pretty good, except the occaisonal one every few months. But still, not bad

When you’re quitting, your friends and family may be eager to help out in any way that they can. Pick your favorite option below or suggest your own. Why would this option be helpful to you? #support• Go places where smoking is not allowed• Send you daily/weekly words of encouragement• Quit smoking with you
Encouragement
Quitting with a friend
#freeyourself
To not be sick when I'm older
Be in good health

Suggested text: Write a list of all the reasons why you want to quit, and post it somewhere prominent where you will frequently see it. Which spot did you choose, and why will it work for you? #reinforcement
I chose my dorm room wall and it could possibly work because I look at it everyday
In my bathroom, cause im always in there a good half hour getting ready.. Lots of time to look at it. :)

data.message: http://www.nova.edu/gsc/nicotine_risk.html Take this test to see just how addicted to nicotine you really are. Post your reaction to your score to this group so we can discuss. Were you surprised? #beingconscious
I got a 1. I'm surprised. The only time i feel the need for one is during work and at night before bed.
I got a 4, which wasn't very surprising. I think stuff like smoking after waking up or after eating has been ingrained into me, making me more dependent by habit.
I got a 1 and I'm surprised because I smoke about ten a day
1.. That's surprising and encouraging
Become more conscious and critique cigarette ads- understand how they try to make their brand appealing. How is Camel trying to manipulate its customers through these ads?  #beingconscious
It's trying to make smoking look sexy and mysterious
Agreed^

For any of you that aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulations. Do any of you feel that if you were a minor, an e-cig would be more appealing and seem “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #beingconscious  http://www.fda.gov/newsevents/publichealthfocus/ucm172906.htm
That's how they make it seem, so I'm sure if they were out while I was kid I would've started earlier. Young minds are impressionable.

Check out this site to see just how much $ you've given to Big Tobacco. Share your numbers here and vow to stop throwing away your hard-earned cash! #beingconscious  http://www.cancer.org/healthy/toolsandcalculators/calculators/app/smoking-cost-calculator.aspx
This link isn't working for me :(

Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have started smoking when you were younger if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #e-cig
Lol i wouldn't have started sooner. I was a wimp and didn't even buy my first pack until 6 months after i turned 18
Yeah I would because it's highly addictive and it reminds me of hookah. Usually people associate e cigarettes as a healthy alternative which is not true.
Oh I'm sure.

data.description: Hi everyone and welcome to the group. Tomorrow, I will be holding the first 'The Doctor Is In' session. You can ask me everything you want to know around smoking, quitting, and the Tobacco Status Project. See you then!

data.message: What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation

I smoke when I'm stressed and in social situations. It's hard not to join when others are smoking around you. But I want to live a healthier lifestyle, and start running. When I smoke and run, I hack my lungs up :(
I agree

Have any of you used a quit program or counseling program to quit before? There are lots of free programs out there- how could these programs benefit you? What would make them better?                       #beingconscious
I think support from others trying to quit helps.
I agree with 10054
On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #motivation
An 8
Thank you all for your active engagement! Your tips and support were awesome and I am sure they were helpful! Today we would like you to comment on two posts today whenever you can. -D'Arius from TSP
Share a Quit Day tip with someone in this group! #support
Try a nicotine replacement
Focusing less on how difficult it is, focusing more on the benefits of quitting, and overall, keeping a positive attitude about quitting as much as possible.
Try not to smoke for three days. It takes three days for nicotine to get out of your system so after that it's all in your head! Also stay away from other smokers for a little while
Chew gum! Or sunflower seeds
My old roommate chews on small straws.. I think anything to keep your mouth occupied. A decent percent of your addiction could be the oral fixation part of it.

Hello Everyone! Today is the day that we will finally begin posting to your group. We encourage you all to be active and comment on as many posts as you can. We also encourage you to talk to the other members of the group and make this experience better. Hope to hear from you all soon!-D'Arius fom TSP

Hello everyone and welcome to the group! We are really excited to be getting started soon. Currently we are waiting for a few more people to join the group, then we will start posting. Looking forward to hearing from all of you! Best,-D'Arius from TSP

This group is for 18-25 year olds who currently smoke and are ready to quit in the very near future. While your quit-date approaches, get educated about Nicotine Replacement Therapies, ways to prepare for and deal with cravings & triggers, grow your support system and learn the best techniques to quit and STAY quit. Please engage with our posts and comment every day!
